  <description type="morphology">Perennials, 10–40 cm. Stems 1–20+, bases relatively thin. Leaf blades narrowly oblanceolate, 4–12 cm × 2–15 mm; mid cauline often reduced to linear or minute bracts. Involucres campanulate, 10–15 × 12–20 mm. Phyllaries ovate to narrowly lanceolate, unequal, 2–14 mm, apices dark brown, obtuse to acute. Paleae 12–18 mm. Florets 20–40; corollas pale pink abaxially, white to yellow adaxially, 15–18 mm. Cypselae 5–6 mm; pappi 4–7 mm. 2n = 18.</description>
  <description type="phenology">Flowering Mar–Aug.</description>
  <description type="habitat">Open limestone areas, roadsides, cliffs, open grassy flats;</description>
  <description type="elevation">50–2600 m;</description>
  <description type="distribution">Ariz., N.Mex., Okla., Tex.; Mexico.</description>
  <number>2.</number>
  <other_name type="common_name">White dandelion or rocklettuce</other_name>
  <discussion>At flowering, phyllaries of Pinaropappus roseus are pale green with margins suffused with pink. On fresh specimens, the dark brown tips are distinctive. Specimens from the mountains of southeastern Arizona and southwestern New Mexico with stems leafy beyond the middles have been recognized as var. foliosus; that trait appears to be widespread and part of the normal range of variation for the species.</discussion>
